@node "introduction" "Introduction"
@next "features"
@prev "copyright"
  The Amiga computers can handle two types of fonts: bitmap- and outline
  fonts. The bitmap fonts can be subdivided in normal bitmap fonts and 
  Colorfonts. The outline fonts (intruduced in OS 2.04) are vector-based,
  so one definition defines all varieties of the font. With the release
  of OS2.04 only CompuGraphic fonts (© Copyright Agfa) could be handled.
  With the introduction of OS 3.0, it is possible to make use of different
  outline font engines: bullet.library for CompuGraphic fonts or
  ATE/post.library for PostScript Type 1 fonts (and CompuGraphic).
  I believe there's also one for TrueType fonts (pre-)released (?!).
  Bitmap fonts are fonts, where each character is represented by one bit-
  plane. Each bit indicates if a pixel is set or not when rendered on the 
  screen. If we use more bitplanes instead of one bitplane, and with the
  addition of a colormap, each combination of bits per pixel indicate
  a color to be rendered on the screen. These multi-bitplane fonts are
  the so-called Colorfonts. Until the introduction of the AA chipset,
  Colorfonts were limited upto 16 colors. The AA chipset (usually in
  combination with OS 3.x), introduced the possibility of Colorfonts with
  up to 256 colors (excluding HAM).

  Bitmap fonts are saved per size. Different sizes of the same fonts are
  stored together in a directory, named after the font, in the FONTS:
  directory.

  ColorFontMaster is a generator-, and editor of Colorfonts (altough normal
  bitmap fonts can also be edited/generated). But as the name suggests,
  Colorfonts are the main thing!
  ColorFontMaster can not edit/generate outline fonts! However, you can
  load them and (with addition of textures, outlines and shade) save them
  as a Colorfont.
  It uses OS 2.04 or better and in case the locale.library is present,
  the program will display its texts in the selected language, otherwise
  the english language is used as a default.

  The main difference between ColorFontMaster and another bitmap font
  editor, is the fact that ColorFontMaster uses an image with glyphs as
  source for the Colorfont, instead of a font file itself. Other editors
  edit the glyphs per character (one per window). ColorFontMaster has the
  advantage that personal drawn images can instantly be converted to Color-
  fonts. Very impressive powerful image processing tools are available 
  for the Amiga. So, creating a fancy, shiny (even raytraced) character-
  set is easily created and converted to a Colorfont using ColorFontMaster!

  Ready made (good quality) Colorfonts are limited available within the PD
  circuit. Very exclusive fonts can be bought from different suppliers
  such as Electronic Arts: the KaraFont series.
  Other Colorfonts (of limited quality) can be found in several PD-series
  and on several CD's (e.g. Multimedia toolkit (1/2), Weird Sience FontCD,
  GigaPD and the Aminet series).
  Many times it is desirable to have the possibility to create your own
  designed Colorfonts for a reasonable price!
  Instead, we get a lot of beautiful bitmap- and outline fonts. It
  would be nice if we could convert these, with the addition of a little
  texture here and there, into multi-coloured fonts: the Colorfonts.
  
  If we do not have the desired Colorfonts, we could also paint them in
  a drawing tool, or let your kid design a new typeface of the alphabet.
  These images, containing the coloured characters can be used to compile
  a text into another image; you just clip them one by one and place them
  in the image according your wishes.
  These images, containing glyphs (coloured), I call PixFonts (I gave it
  that name; who knows, it might become a standard!).
  These PixFonts are widely available in the Public-Domain circuit.
  Most of them are to be used in demo-maker programs or video titlers.
  Very good PixFonts can be found in the PD series: Exile Fonts, Dynamite
  Fonts, Gelignite Fonts, WS-Fonts CD, EM Compugraphic CD's and various
  PD-CD's. Most of the PixFonts in this distribution are taken from PD-CD's.

  Some people, and these are especially video-phanatics, want black and 
  white fonts which are anti-aliased with grey-scale tints: so these
  are in fact Colorfonts. They look as normal black and white fonts but
  without rough edges. These edges are smoothed with grey colours!
  It is possible to generate these high-quality video fonts with Color-
  FontMaster!
  
  ColorFontMaster (CFM) can handle all generation varieties of Colorfonts:
@{b}      - Create Colorfonts out of single bitmap/outline fonts and extrude-,
        edge- and fill them with brushes or textures.
      - Edit existing Colorfonts into new ones.
      - Create Colorfonts out of any (type of) image (PixFonts), where the 
        glyphs are drawn and you just have to clip them.
      - Draw your own Colorfonts in the ColorFontMaster editor.@{ub}

  All this can be done, using ColorFontMaster !
@endnode

@node "features" "Features"
@next "readthis"
@prev "introduction"
ColorFontMaster is:
    - capable of generating Colorfonts with 2 colors up to 256 colors!
    - fully OS 2.x and 3.x compatible. DOES NOT RUN UNDER 1.x !!
    - fully localized! Included are: english (default), nederlands and
      deutsch.
    - supporting proportional font generation (can be switched off)!
    - Under OS 3.x and above: loading by DataTypes.
    - AA colormap handling fully respected.
    - offering you to load ANY size picture containing your own drawn
      coloured characters upto various sizes and convert them into a Color-
      font.
    - OS 3.x with AA chipset offers editing in 32-bits color per gun.
    - able to preset the font contents, without having to 'delete'
      characters of the existing font (Ideal for making demo-fonts
      or just to preserve valuable disk-space).
    - selectable to use ASL- or ReqTools file selectors!
    - AmigaGuide® supported (documentation included).
    - processing user startup settings by ToolTypes and preferences.
    - capable of scaling Colorfonts!!!
    - offering programmers to include Colorfonts in C programs, by 
      generating C-code of the Colorfont.
    - equiped with a comfortable editor, with pixel precise settings
      of proportional variables.
    - equiped with a Pix/Colorfont generator: make your own (Pix) fonts
      of existing bitmap/outline fonts and colorize them with textures,
      outlines and extrude them in any direction you want.
    - able to quantisize (reduce colors) a picture to less colors.
    - able to remap colormaps.
    - able to edit existing fonts.
    - able to save patterns, to be able to use again for generating a 
      Colorfont.
    - configuring automatically the PAL/NTSC modes.
    - offering image processing utilities for brightness/contrast, 
      embossing ,convolution etc. and even generation of grey-scaled
      anti-aliased Colorfonts!
@endnode

@node "readthis" "*Read This*"
@next "starting"
@prev "features"

  This documentation is written for the english (built-in) version
  of ColorFontMaster.

  This program is Localized:
  The Amiga can be operated in many different languages.
  Several files must be copied to your hard drive for each language
  supported. ColorFontMaster has such files built-in (english) and on
  disk: nederlands and deutsch.

  Design decision:
  With the introduction of AGA graphics and Kickstart 3.0, it became
  possible to write code for handling colors with a precision of 32-
  bits per gun (red, green and blue) instead of 4 bits on non-AGA
  machines. If your Amiga is booted up normally, your Amiga will start-
  up in AGA mode (mostly via C:SetPatch : make sure your startup-sequence
  contains this call!)
  Each color can be handled more accurate than before but still: CBM did
  not change the ColorFont specifications to give the fonts also an
  accuracy of 32 bits! It is still the 4!
  Anyway, I made the decision to work in 32bits-per-gun mode. Your pictures
  will be saved as 32 bits/gun and your Colorfonts with 4 bits/gun.

@endnode

@node "starting" "Starting ColorFontMaster"
@next "controlwindow"
@prev "introduction"
  It is possible to start CFM from the shell window and from the WorkBench.

  @{b}Shell@{ub}:
        cfm [<picture name>]
  This causes CFM to be started. If the optional picture name is given,
  CFM will directly display the selected picture.
  If the picture name is invalid, a requester pops up, giving you the
  opportunity to start ColorFontMaster without a picture (select Continue)
  or cancel the whole operation.

 @{b} WorkBench@{ub}:
  ColorFontMaster interpretes a number of ToolTypes, which enables you to
  define a convenience start-up of the program. The ToolTypes can be 
  entered or edited in the Workbench, by selecting the icon of ColorFont-
  Master and selecting the Menu option 'Icons/Information...'. For further
  details about the editing and saving of ToolTypes, reference is made to
  the Workbench User Manual of your computer, chapter "Icon Tool Types".

  @{fg shine}ICONIC@{fg text}   - This ToolType starts up ColorFontMaster in iconized form,
      i.e. the @{"application icon" link "gworkbench" 0} of ColorFontMaster will be
      placed on the Workbench. To start ColorFontMaster up, just double-
      click on the applocation icon.

  @{fg shine}NO_AA@{fg text}   - This ToolType is only important to people, owning an AGA
      machine, like the A1200 and A4000. ColorFontMaster tries to support
      the AA chips as best as possible. This means colors are internally
      represented as 32 bits values instead of 4 bits. Use is made of
      specific V39 (OS 3.0) calls. If you want to operate like anyone
      with a pre-AGA machine: use this ToolType.
      The reason for doing this might be the fact that the machine is
      able to work with extended colormaps; Colorfonts are still limited
      to the old-fashioned 4bit (0x0RGB) format! So: what you see is what
      you get.

  @{fg shine}SYSTEM=<name>@{fg text}   - Some people feel the need to perform specific
      actions after saving a Colorfont. This might be e.g. FixFonts or
      update your private font-cache. This ToolType specifies the execu- 
      table that will be executed after saving a font. This program must
      be in the ColorFontMaster: directory or specified by a full path.
      Default nothing is used.
      e.g.:          SYSTEM=FixFonts
                     SYSTEM=Work:Systems/MyOwnTool
      If you specify SYSTEM=
      (nothing behind the '=' sign!) no executable will be called.
      Note: before executing, you will always be asked for confirmation!

  @{fg shine}XFONT@{fg text}=x
  @{fg shine}YFONT@{fg text}=y  - These two ToolTypes define the default size of the font in
      ColorFontMaster. If these ToolTypes are not defined, a value of 16 
      (both x and y) is valid. Minimum size is 4 and maximum size is 300
      (LoRes) or 600 (HiRes).

  @{fg shine}BASELINE@{fg text}=b This ToolType defines the baseline of the font.
      Minimum is 0 and the maximum is YFONT-1.

  @{fg shine}WIDTH@{fg text}=w
  @{fg shine}HEIGHT@{fg text}=h
  @{fg shine}DEPTH@{fg text}=d  - These ToolTypes define the startup screen dimensions,
      where WIDTH is default 320, HEIGHT is default 200 and DEPTH is 
      default 2 (4 colors).

  @{fg shine}SCREEN@{fg text}=PAL
  @{fg shine}SCREEN@{fg text}=NTSC - This ToolType determines if you want to work in a PAL
      (European standard) or an NTSC (American) screen. The total height
      of a PAL screen is 256 pixels and the screen height of an NTSC screen
      is 200 pixels.

  @{fg shine}PIXDIR@{fg text}=<string> - This ToolType defines the directory, in which
      ColorFontMaster assumes the PixFonts will be sited.

  @{fg shine}TEXDIR@{fg text}=<string> - This ToolType defines the directory, in which
      ColorFontMaster assumes the textures for the 'Font Maker' will be
      sited.

  @{fg shine}BRSDIR@{fg text}=<string> - This ToolType defines the directory, in which
      ColorFontMaster assumes the brushes for the 'Font Editor' (and Maker)
      will be sited.
                          
  @{fg shine}COLDIR@{fg text}=<string> - This ToolType defines the directory, in which
      ColorFontMaster assumes the colormaps will be sited.

  @{fg shine}CNVDIR@{fg text}=<string> - This ToolType defines the directory, in which
      ColorFontMaster assumes the convolution kernels will be sited.

  @{fg shine}PATDIR@{fg text}=<string> - This ToolType defines the directory, in which
      ColorFontMaster assumes the Patterns will be sited.

  @{b}To start CFM without a picture@{ub}:
     Double-click on the CFM icon on the WorkBench. Starting up CFM,
     results in an empty screen and the CFM control-window. 

  @{b}To start CFM with a picture@{ub}:
     Click once on the CFM icon. Hold down the SHIFT key and double-click
     on the icon of a picture. CFM will directly display the picture.
        
    If a file is selected, the picture is loaded and displayed as LO-RES 
    or HI-RES (according the file format) with a height (on PAL monitors) 
    of 200 pixels. HAM pictures are not supported yet!
    TIP:@{i} If you suspected a HIRES picture and the loaded file is displayed
         as a LORES picture, then the width of the picture was propably
         smaller than 640 pixels. To display it in HIRES: select the option
         @{ui}Edit/Dimensions@{i} and select the Hires screenmode. Accept
         the new screen (do not scale!).@{ui}

    Note: @{i}If the picture is bigger, you can scroll through the picture by
          using the cursor keys or place the mouse pointer in the picture 
          and move the mouse while holding the left mouse button down
          (panning).@{ui}

    The lower part of the screen, shows the ColorFontMaster @{"control window" link "controlwindow" 0}
    (with the version number in the window title).
    All major functions are presented as gadgets.
@endnode

@node "controlwindow" "Control window"
@next "menus"
@prev "introduction"

    The @{"control-window" system "vilbm cfmControl.pic"} consists of the following parts:

        @{" Width           " link "size" 0}
        @{" Height          " link "size" 0}
        @{" Baseline        " link "baseline" 0}
        @{" Grid            " link "grid" 0} 
        @{" Character select" link "select" 0}
        @{" Origin          " link "origin" 0}
        @{" Adv.            " link "advance" 0}
        @{" Character width " link "width" 0}
@endnode

@node "size" "Height and Width"
Height and width

    The input-field plus slider marked 'H:' stands for the height and
    the input-field plus slider marked 'W:' stands for the width.

    At startup of ColorFontMaster, a character-box is drawn in its initial
    position, i.e. (0,0). The height and width of the box stands for
    the heigth and the maximum width of the characters to be defined 
    (initial:16 or defined by the @{"ToolTypes WIDTH and/or HEIGHT" link "starting" 0}
    or preferences).
    Manual changing of the height and width can be performed by entering
    new values in these fields or sliding the prop to the required
    value. The arrow buttons can be used to step up or step down 1 pixel.
    These values cover all characters within a font.

    Another way is to press the 'H:' or 'W:' button:
    Selecting one of these buttons, makes it possible to define the
    Height and Width of a font with the use of the mouse.
    After selecting the button a cross-hair cursor will be drawn, with its
    intersection at the mouse-pointer. 
    Pressing the left-mouse button, removes the cross-hair and a box
    will be drawn on the picture. Keeping the left-mouse button pressed,
    enables you to resize this box to the desired format finishing at the
    time the button is released.
    During this 'capture', the current height and width of the box will
    be updated in the Height and Width fields. Releasing the left-mouse
    button, results in the updated selected heigth and width in the
    control window.
    During the capture-mode, this option can be de-selected by
    pressing the <ESC> key: ColorFontMaster returns to its state as
    left before selecting the capture-mode.
@endnode

@node "baseline" "BaseLine"
@{fg shine}    Baseline@{fg text}

    An input field plus arrow-buttons and a slider marked 'Bsl:', stands
    for the Baseline. This is a term for the position at which a glyph
    is sited (y-position). All text printed into a window is positioned
    releative to this y-position. You can change the baseline by sliding
    the prop to the required position. The character-box in the picture
    shows the current baseline: it is the horizontal line, drawn within
    the character box (default: Height-1 or as defined by the preferences
    or the @{"ToolType BASELINE" link "starting" 0}).
@endnode

@node "grid" "Grid"
        Select one of the following options:

        @{" Grid " link "gridsel" 0}
        @{" Show " link "shgrid" 0}
@endnode

@node "gridsel" "Grid"
@{fg shine}Grid (Keyboard: G)@{fg text}

    Default, the grid selection is activated. This means that
    if you move your character-box by means of the cursor keys
    within the picture, the box will be moved with margins that 
    corresponds to the height and width. Deselecting the grid-
    option, results in moving only one pixel at a time by using
    the cursor keys. This enables you to put the character-box 
    very accurate within the picture.
    This option is most helpful in times when you 'captured' the
    heigth and width, but not accurate enough on a glyph.
@endnode

@node "shgrid" "Show"
@{fg shine}Show (Keyboard: H)@{fg text}

    Selecting this button results in drawing the complete grid on the
    font picture. This helps you to decide if the character-box
    position is accurate enough for more than one character. Selecting
    this button again or selecting any other option in ColorFontMaster
    removes the grid from the picture.
@endnode

@node "origin" "Origin"
@{fg shine}Origin (Keyboard: O)@{fg text}

   Selecting this button results in attaching the character-box to
   the mouse pointer when the pointer is moved over the image.
   Pressing the left-mouse button places the character-box on the
   screen without adjusting the width or height.
   Character-box movement is now performed relative to this selected
   position.
   During the 'Origin' mode, this option can be deselected by
   pressing the <ESC> key: ColorFontMaster returns to its state as
   left before selecting 'Origin'.
@endnode

@node "select" "Selecting/deleting a character"
    @{fg shine}Selection of a character:@{fg text}
    1 The character-slider is divided into steps, where every step
      stands for a character from the ASCII range of characters going from 
      ASCII=32 to ASCII=255 except for the range ASCII=128 to ASCII=159 
      Sliding the prop updates the character in the text field.
    2 You can also enter the required character directly in the text
      field. (This field operates in overwrite mode, so deleting cha-
      racters is not necessary). The position of the prop of the slider
      is updated to its corresponding position.
    3 The third and easiest way, is to select the button 'Select'. It pops
      up a window with all the characters. Select the desired one... done!
      If you select a character which was already defined, the character-
      box will be placed on the corresponding position in the image.

    After selecting the character and placing the character-box on the
    prefered place, the character can be defined by selecting the 'Set'
    button. This action results in creating the character internally
    into a pattern, preserving location and ASCII code. Now, the charac-
    ter-width of the character can be set with the width-slider,
    and/or value-field (labelled 'W:').

@{fg highlight}    Important note:
    The 'width' as presented behind the 'W:' button stands for the global
    width: i.e. the maximum width of all characters within a font. This
    width will be used by the system in case a font is saved as fixed-
    width: non-proportional!
    The width as presented behind the 'W:' label stands for the local
    width: i.e. the width of that particular character! In case the font
    is saved as proportional, this width will be used by the system.
@{fg text}
    If a position of the character box matches the position of an 
    already defined character, the slider is NOT set to the corres-
    ponding position of that character and the text field is NOT 
    displaying that character (only in case of selection by cursor
    keys or 'Origin'.
    This means, that you can reselect a defined character again by
    moving the character-box to its desired location and select 'Set'.
           
    If a defined character is selected and you want to delete that 
    character from the pattern of the Colorfont, select 'Clear'.
@endnode

@node "advance" "Adv."
@next "main"
@{fg shine}Advance (Keyboard: A)@{fg text}

   Selecting 'Adv.' (advance) is used for moving the character-box
   each time a character is selected by means of 'Set'. 
   The movement is performed according to the selected height and 
   width. 
   The character box is always positioned to the right, until it
   reaches the right border. (if the picture size is bigger than
   the screen you're looking at, the picture is scrolled in a way
   that you always can see the character box). The next position
   will be at the left border, with a distance equal to the font 
   height, downwards. 
   If the characters in the image are placed in a sequence (ASCII
   code), it will never be necessary to position the character-box!
   Look at '32 Point Font' in the 'PixFonts' directory. All characters
   are placed in a row-column manner with the same distance (=32)
   (check with '@{"Show" link "shgrid" 0}').
   In this case it is possible to use the pattern 'rsi32*32.cfm'
   If 'Adv.' is switched off, the character-box will not be positioned
   after selecting 'Set'.
   In case all characters are scattered all over the picture, you
   better switch this option off.
@endnode

@node "menus" "The Program Menus"
@next "main"
